m. de marco



 m. de marco
to talk at a distance, when you have nothing to say, though you were
ever so near; to go fast from this place to that, with nothing to do either 
at one or the other:  these are powers certainly. - john ruskin

 miss de marco is a fourth-year graduate student in the department of mathematics and computer science at wesleyan university in scenic middletown, connecticut.  she is studying linear logic and logic programming under professor james lipton.  for your surfing pleasure, she has provided a small assortment of poems:


em portugu&ecircs:

 on the value of higher education: liberdade by fernando pessoa
 the final word on love: amor &eacute fogo que arde sem se ver by luis de cam&otildees


poetry of the industrial revolution:

 the cry of the children and more by elizabeth barrett browning
 a selection from book eighth of the excursion by william wordsworth
 christina rossetti on the onset of winter
 songs of education:  part iii by gilbert keith chesterton.  (for more information on chesterton or distributism, please proceed to the g. k. chesterton page.)





